Quality Control and Filtering¶

Identification of individuals with elevated missing data rates or outlying heterozygosity rate¶

We want to filter out all samples that has a high rate of missing data, since that can be due low DNA quality. Furthermore, we want to filter samples with either high or low heterozygosity rate, since this could be a result of contamination of the sample. Both of these will bias the result.

To identify missing data rates, we run the following command from the shell prompt:

plink --bfile eye_color --missing --allow-no-sex --out eye_color

This will output a file eyecolor.imiss, where the number and proportion of missing SNPs can be found.

To identify heterozygosity rate, we run the following command:

plink --bfile eye_color --het --allow-no-sex --out eye_color

This will output a file eyecolor.het, where the number of homozygous genotypes (Hom), along with the number of non-missing genotypes per individual (NM), are specified. The observed heterozygosity rate per individual can then be calculated as:

  • Het = (NM − Hom)/NM
In [81]:
d_miss <- read.table("eye_color.imiss",header=T)
d_het <- read.table("eye_color.het",header=T)
d <- inner_join(d_miss,d_het)

d <- d %>% 
    mutate(Het = (N.NM.-O.HOM.)/N.NM.)

Identification of duplicated or related individuals¶

We also want to filter related individuals and to do this, we calculate an identity by descent (IBD) matrix. This can be done using PLINK, but it works best with non-correlated SNPs. Therefore, we prune the data such that no SNP pair has an r^2 value above some threshold. We do that using the following command:

plink --bfile eye_color --indep-pairwise 500kb 5 0.2 --out eye_color

This will output a file eye_color.prune.in with the independent SNPs. This file can now be used to calculate IBD between each pair of individuals. The following PLINK command is used:

plink --bfile eye_color --extract eye_color.prune.in --genome --min 0.09 --out eye_color

This will output a file eye_color.genome. The calculated IBD will only be printet in this file if it is above 0.09 (mean value between third degree relatives (0.125), and fourth degree relatives (0.0625)). PI_HAT shows how much of the genome two individuals share. 1 = identical twins, 0.5 = siblings.

We use this command to filter away variants that deviate more from HW than p<1e-5. I also filter minor allele frequence of less than 0.01 and remove SNPs with a call rate less than 0.25 (--geno option)

plink --bfile eye_color --remove wrong_ibd.txt --geno 0.75 --hwe 0.00001 --maf 0.01 --make-bed --out eye_color-QC

Now we have 837498 variants and 1260 people left in the dataset. In total we have filtered for related individuals, strong deviation from HW, minor allele frequency less than set treshold and SNPs with call rate less than treshold.

PCA¶

It is best to do PCA on an LD-pruned set of SNPs. Therefore, we use the follwing command to prune the dataset:

plink --bfile eye_color-QC --indep-pairwise 500kb 5 0.2 --out eye_color-QC

This creates a .prune.in and a .prune.out file. Now, to use the pruned SNPs to calculate a relationship matrix and the first 20 PCs, we run this command:

plink --bfile eye_color-QC --extract eye_color-QC.prune.in --pca 20 --out eye_color-QC

This calculates the eigenvalues and eigenvectors.

Association testing using PLINK¶

Test for association with eyecolor status using a Fisher’s exact test¶

To do the Fisher's exact test, we type the following command:

plink --bfile eye_color-QC --assoc fisher --allow-no-sex --pheno brown_vs_rest.txt --out brown_vs_rest

This produces a brown_vs_rest.assoc.fisher output file.

Adjusting for PCs¶

We can use logistic regression test to perform an association test while correcting for covariates. To include the first 2 PCs as a covariate we type:

plink --bfile eye_color-QC --pheno brown_vs_rest.txt --allow-no-sex --logistic --covar eye_color-QC.eigenvec --covar-number 1-2

The output file plink.assoc.logistic contains p-values for both the SNPs and the covariates.

Estimating heritability¶

Calculating genetic relationsship matrix¶

We use the following plink command to calculate the genetic relationship matrix (GRM):

plink --make-grm-gz --bfile eye_color-QC --pheno brown_vs_rest.txt --allow-no-sex --out eye_color-QC

This outputs the GRM in the file eye_color-QC.grm.gz.

Estimating variance components¶

We now use the package gcta to estimate how much of the variance in the phenotype is explained by the SNPs. The command looks like this:

gcta64 --grm-gz eye_color-QC --pheno brown_vs_rest.txt --reml --out test

and outputs test.hsq which contains a summary of the restricted maximum likelihood (REML) analysis.

Mixed models¶

I will try to use the GCTA package with the gcta-mlm function to do mixed linear model based association analysis. To start out I compute the GRM. This computes binary files to be used later.

plink --make-grm-bin --bfile eye_color-QC --pheno brown_vs_rest.txt --allow-no-sex --out eye_color-QC

Then I run this GCTA command to do the MLM analysis:

gcta64 --mlma --bfile eye_color-QC --grm eye_color-QC --pheno brown_vs_rest.txt --autosome --out eye_color-QC --thread-num 10

which outputs this file eye_color-QC.mlma.

Now I want to try to investigate if any of the SNPs i've found, is in close proximity to the ones in the article.

In [73]:
find_close_genes <- function(x_away){
    
    sign_SNPs <- most_significant %>% 
        mutate(ref_closest = NA,
               ref_pos = NA,
               ref_Nearest.Gene = NA,
               ref_P = NA)

    gene_pos <- tibble(Pos = article_genes$Pos,
                       Chr = article_genes$Chr,
                       RS = article_genes$RS,
                       Nearest.Gene = article_genes$Nearest.Gene,
                       P = article_genes$P)

    for (i in 1:nrow(sign_SNPs)) {
    
        pos <- sign_SNPs$bp[i]
        chr <- sign_SNPs$Chr[i]
        test <- gene_pos$Chr == chr & gene_pos$Pos-x_away <= pos & pos <= gene_pos$Pos+x_away
    
        close_rs <- gene_pos$RS[which(test)]
        ref_pos <- gene_pos$Pos[which(test)]
        gene <- gene_pos$Nearest.Gene[which(test)]
        p_val <- gene_pos$P[which(test)]
    
        sign_SNPs$ref_closest[i] <- list(close_rs)
        sign_SNPs$ref_pos[i] <- unique(ref_pos)[1]
        sign_SNPs$ref_Nearest.Gene[i] <- list(unique(gene))
        sign_SNPs$ref_P[i] <- list(unique(p_val))
    
    }
    
    sign_SNPs <- sign_SNPs %>% 
        drop_na()
    
    return(sign_SNPs)
}
